# AICADS isolation contract (consumer side)

This project consumes `@ai-ds/core`. The design system **owns** the
behavior layer (Radix, cmdk, vaul, sonner, Floating UI, input-otp,
class-variance-authority). Consumer code **never** imports any of those
engines directly — always go through the AICADS semantic surface.

## Allowed

```ts
import { Button, Modal, Tabs } from '@ai-ds/core/components';
import { Modal } from '@ai-ds/core/components/Modal';
import { toast, Toaster } from '@ai-ds/core/components/Toast';
import { ScrollArea } from '@ai-ds/core/shared';
import { useBreakpoint } from '@ai-ds/core/hooks';
```

## Forbidden in consumer code

```ts
import * as Dialog from '@radix-ui/react-dialog';          //  blocked
import { Command } from 'cmdk';                            //  blocked
import { Drawer } from 'vaul';                             //  blocked
import { toast } from 'sonner';                            //  blocked
import { useFloating } from '@floating-ui/react';          //  blocked
import { OTPInput } from 'input-otp';                      //  blocked
import { cva } from 'class-variance-authority';            //  blocked
```

Reach the same functionality via the equivalent AICADS primitive
(`Modal`, `CommandPalette`, `Drawer`, `Toaster` + `toast()`, `Popover`,
`PinInput`, contract-driven appearance respectively).

## Why

The AICADS `_internal/` adapters are the **single** place where each
engine is touched. Bypassing them couples your consumer code to a
specific engine, breaks the isolation contract, and prevents the design
system from swapping engines without consumer churn.

## Lint enforcement

The same rule is enforced by ESLint via the shareable config at
`@ai-ds/core/eslint-config`. Add it to your consumer project:

```js
// .eslintrc.cjs
module.exports = {
  extends: [require.resolve('@ai-ds/core/eslint-config')],
};
```
